  "prompt": "Who invented immunofluorescence? What purpose does it serve?",
  "response": "Immunofluorescence was first developed by Albert Coons and his colleagues in 1941 while working at Harvard Medical School. \n\nPurpose of immunofluorescence:\n1. Detect and localize specific proteins/antigens in biological samples\n2. Visualize cellular structures and molecular interactions\n3. Used in medical diagnostics and research\n4. Allows precise identification of specific molecules within cells or tissues\n5. Enables researchers to study protein distribution, cellular localization, and interactions\n\nThere are two main types of immunofluorescence:\n- Direct immunofluorescence: Uses a single labeled antibody\n- Indirect immunofluorescence: Uses a primary antibody and a fluorescent secondary antibody\n\nCommon applications include:\n- Cancer research\n- Identifying infectious agents\n- Studying protein expression\n- Analyzing cellular structures\n- Diagnosing autoimmune diseases\n- Tracking cellular processes\n\nThe technique uses fluorescent dyes (fluorochromes) attached to antibodies that specifically bind to target molecules, making them visible under a fluorescence microscope. This allows researchers to see precise locations and quantities of specific proteins or antigens within biological samples.",
